<br>
The Theologian's Dilemma is an &quot;old, tired excuse&quot;? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
I don't see it as &quot;an excuse&quot; but as strong evidence that there <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a god, certainly not an all-loving god.  If god exists, he can't possibly be all loving when you look at all the awfulness of the world he supposedly made. (As Gaia points out, the OT is pretty clear that he's not always been characterized as all-loving.) <br>
<br>
But this sentimentalized sweetie-pie Jesus character IS supposed to be all-loving. Yet bad things happen continually to us in this imperfect world he supposedly created for us. If it's not legitimate to even <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>question</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that, then how come all of you Christians are constantly trying to cover for this theological shortcoming by proclaiming that all the bad that happens is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>the Lord's way of teaching us lessons</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - or bringing us to our knees to make us more teachable or more dependent on him?<br>
<br>
As I asked Shirene earlier, is he in control or is he not? You can't have it both ways.<br>
<br>
